Thesis
The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986

The study of racial disparity in the criminal justice system has been widely recognized as a complex and sensitive issue that has indelibly influenced sentencing outcomes for Black men. With the passage of the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986, new Federal mandatory minimum guidelines recognized the 100:1 crack-powder cocaine sentencing disparity which set into motion an era of aggressive policies. This research analyzes the effects of mandatory minimum sentencing laws embedded in the ADAA of 1986, while establishing the inconsistencies with aggressive policing and the ramifications associated with racial discrimination. Critical Race Theory is used as an analytic, explanatory, and conceptual instrument in the study, while providing a necessary understanding of the framework used in identifying and examining the differences between the sentencing disparity in relation to socioeconomic status and race. The analysis of this policy introduces previous and current research to examine the power structures and systemic oppression that perpetuate racial inequities in order to identify and develop strategies for action and change. The preponderance of evidence suggests that the association of race and sentencing outcomes continues to operate through policies and practices inundated within social systems, structures, and institutions that systematically reflect and produce racial inequalities.

